Emergency patients arrive at the hospital without ever being scheduled in advance, and are traditionally modeled as Poisson random variables in the literature [51], with a time-varying arrival rate. The arrival rate should be determined for each period, and should thus vary across time. Let the expected number of arrivals on period s, where d + 1 ≤ s ≤ t, of patient type u ∈ U, where U represents the number of emergency patient types indexed by u, be represented by λu(s), and the probability of staying exactly h nights be represented by fu(h), where fu(0) = 0 for all u. Let Fu(h) be the CDF of fu(h), and Ru(h) = 1 − Fu(h). Because both thinning and summing Poisson random variables produces a Poisson random variable, the sum of the expected remaining patients from each previous period’s arrivals is the expected value of a Poisson-distributed variable of the total remaining emergency patients. The number of future emergency patients present at period t, when forecasted from period d, represented by Poisson random variable \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
